---
import ArticleLayout from '../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="Get Started for Zero Cost"
  description="Any rucksack, books for weight, whatever shoes you've got. Everything you need to start loaded walking today without spending a penny."
  type="guide"
>

<div class="article-body max-w-3xl mx-auto py-8">

  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <p><strong>You don't need to buy anything.</strong> A rucksack you already own, some weight from around the house, and whatever shoes you walk in today. That's a loaded walk. You can refine the gear later if you want to — but you can start right now.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The rucksack</h2>

  <p>Any backpack works. A school bag, a hiking daypack, a laptop rucksack, an old travel bag. The only thing that matters at the start is that it sits reasonably close to your back and has two shoulder straps.</p>

  <p>A few things to check before you load it up:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tighten the straps</strong> so the bag sits high on your back, not swinging around at hip level. The weight should be between your shoulder blades, not pulling you backwards from your lower back.</li>
    <li><strong>Check the seams.</strong> Give the shoulder straps a firm tug where they meet the bag. If the stitching looks thin or is already fraying, go easy on the weight.</li>
    <li><strong>Use the chest strap</strong> if it has one. It stops the shoulder straps sliding outward and makes a surprising difference to comfort.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout-warn">
    <p><strong>A word about durability.</strong> Regular rucksacks aren't designed for repeated heavy loads. The shoulder strap stitching is the weak point — it'll hold up fine for a few weeks of moderate weight, but if you're loading 10kg+ several times a week, the seams will wear. That's not a reason to buy something expensive before you know you enjoy this. It's just something to be aware of. Check the stitching every few sessions.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The weight</h2>

  <p>You need something heavy in the bag. Here are things most people already have:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Books.</strong> A couple of hardbacks are typically 1-2kg each. Easy to adjust by adding or removing one. Stack them flat against the back panel of the bag so the weight sits close to your spine.</li>
    <li><strong>Water bottles.</strong> A 1-litre bottle weighs 1kg. Predictable, easy to scale, and you can drink it if you get thirsty. Fill a few and pack them tightly so they don't shift around.</li>
    <li><strong>Bags of soil or compost.</strong> A small bag of garden soil is cheap and heavy. Double-bag it (put it inside a bin liner or second bag) so if it leaks you're not walking home with a muddy back. A 5kg bag of compost from a garden centre costs under £3 and is the right shape for a rucksack.</li>
    <li><strong>Sand.</strong> Same principle as soil. A bag of play sand or builder's sand, double-bagged. Very dense — a small bag goes a long way.</li>
    <li><strong>Rice or flour.</strong> A 2kg bag of rice from the kitchen cupboard works perfectly and is already sealed.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The key thing is to <strong>keep the weight from shifting</strong>. If books or bottles are sliding around inside the bag, they'll pull you off balance and make the walk uncomfortable. Pack tightly, fill gaps with a towel or jumper, and make sure everything sits as a single stable block against the back of the bag.</p>

  <h2>How much weight to start with</h2>

  <p>Start lighter than you think. You're going to walk for 30-45 minutes, and weight that feels fine in your kitchen will feel very different after 20 minutes of walking.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Never done this before?</strong> Start with 4-6kg (roughly 9-13 lbs). That's two large hardback books and a bottle of water.</li>
    <li><strong>Reasonably active?</strong> Start with 6-10kg (roughly 13-22 lbs).</li>
    <li><strong>Already strong?</strong> Start with 10-12kg (roughly 22-26 lbs) and adjust from there.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>A good rule: if the weight is changing your posture — making you lean forward, hunch your shoulders, or take shorter steps — it's too heavy. Reduce it. You should be able to walk with your normal gait, just working a bit harder.</p>

  <p>Use the <a href={`${base}/load-up`}>Load Up calculator</a> to find a more precise starting weight based on your body weight, age, and target heart rate zone.</p>

  <h2>The shoes</h2>

  <p>Whatever you walk in today is fine to start with. Trainers, walking shoes, even sturdy casual shoes. The added weight on your back does increase the force through your feet, but at beginner weights (4-10kg) it's a modest increase that your current footwear can handle.</p>

  <p>A few things to think about:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Trainers</strong> (running shoes, gym shoes) work well on pavement and smooth paths. Good cushioning, flexible, comfortable. Less ideal on loose gravel or wet grass where you want more grip.</li>
    <li><strong>Walking shoes or trail shoes</strong> are better for mixed terrain. More grip, stiffer sole, better ankle support. If you already own a pair, use them.</li>
    <li><strong>Walking boots</strong> give the most ankle support and best grip on rough ground, but they're heavier and can cause blisters if you haven't broken them in.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The most important thing at the start is that your shoes are <strong>comfortable for the distance you're planning to walk without any extra weight</strong>. If a shoe gives you blisters on a normal walk, adding a loaded pack will make it worse, not better.</p>

  <p>Read the <a href={`${base}/guides/footwear`}>full footwear guide</a> for more detail on socks, blister prevention, and what to look for if you do decide to buy something.</p>

  <h2>The route</h2>

  <p>Start on familiar ground. A route you already know, on terrain you're comfortable with. Pavement or well-maintained paths are ideal for your first few sessions — predictable surface, easy to maintain a steady pace.</p>

  <p>Flat is fine. Don't seek out hills on your first outing. Hills increase your heart rate significantly, and you want to get a feel for how the weight alone affects your effort before adding gradient.</p>

  <p>If possible, choose a loop rather than an out-and-back route. That way, if the weight feels too heavy at the halfway point, you're heading home rather than facing the same distance back.</p>

  <h2>The walk itself</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Pack your bag</strong> and put it on. Walk around the house for a minute. Does it feel stable? Is anything shifting? Adjust before you leave.</li>
    <li><strong>Start walking at your normal pace.</strong> Don't try to walk fast. The weight will raise your heart rate naturally.</li>
    <li><strong>After 10 minutes, check in.</strong> How's your breathing? Can you speak in full sentences? If you can, you're probably in or near zone 2. If you're gasping, slow down.</li>
    <li><strong>At the halfway point, check your shoulders and posture.</strong> Are you hunching? Consciously pull your shoulders back and down. Engage your core lightly.</li>
    <li><strong>When you get home, note how you feel.</strong> Tired but fine? Good — same weight next time, maybe a bit longer. Exhausted? Drop 2kg next time. Barely noticed it? Add 2kg.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>That's it</h2>

  <p>Rucksack. Weight. Shoes you own. A route you know. Thirty minutes.</p>

  <p>If you enjoyed it, do it again in two days. If it felt too heavy, reduce the weight. If it felt too easy, add a book. The progression is simple and you control it completely.</p>

  <p>Everything else — heart rate monitors, proper rucking packs, structured programmes — is refinement. It makes the process better and more precise. But it's not required. The most important thing is to load up and walk out the door.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>Ready to get more precise?</strong> Use <a href={`${base}/find-your-zone`}>Find Your Zone 2</a> to calculate your personal heart rate range, then <a href={`${base}/load-up`}>Load Up</a> to find the ideal weight and pace for your body. Or just keep walking and adjust by feel — that works too.</p>
  </div>
</div>

</ArticleLayout>
